From 43c6d79fdd9e79a6332fd9495e1654080ebb6857 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
Date: Thu, 10 Jul 2025 12:31:44 +0530
Subject: [PATCH] CVE-2018-5709

---
 ROOT-SECURITY-RELEASE.md | 49 +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
 1 file changed, 49 insertions(+)
 create mode 100644 ROOT-SECURITY-RELEASE.md

diff --git a/ROOT-SECURITY-RELEASE.md b/ROOT-SECURITY-RELEASE.md
new file mode 100644
index 000000000..50043ea8c
--- /dev/null
+++ b/ROOT-SECURITY-RELEASE.md
@@ -0,0 +1,49 @@
+## Why Vulnerabilities in `krb5` Are Often Not Fixable in Containers
+
+Security scanners (e.g., Trivy, Grype) flag vulnerabilities in `krb5` based on:
+
+- Version numbers of `krb5` libraries and binaries
+- CVEs listed in NVD, Debian Tracker, or vendor feeds
+
+However, these detections are often **false positives** or **non-exploitable in containerized setups**, because they:
+
+- Flag versions even when a patch has been **backported** (common in Debian/Red Hat)
+- Ignore service exposure: `krb5kdc` is rarely exposed in containers
+- Fail to detect whether the vulnerable code path is ever reachable in your application
+
+Manually replacing or patching `krb5` inside a container:
+
+- Risks breaking core authentication or PAM integration
+- Can cause undefined behavior in dependent services (e.g., SSH, LDAP, NFS)
+- Violates distro integrity and can break automated package management
+
+---
+
+---
+
+## 📌 CVE-2018-5709 – NULL Dereference in `krb5kdc` (False Positive)
+
+- **Component:** MIT Kerberos KDC (`krb5kdc`)
+- **Issue:** NULL pointer dereference when processing an unauthenticated AS-REQ containing a `PA-SUPPORTED-ENCTYPES` value
+- **Impact:** May cause a crash (denial of service) in the Key Distribution Center (KDC), but **no remote code execution or privilege escalation**
+- **Upstream Status:** ❗ Not treated as a security vulnerability  
+  → [Debian Security Tracker](https://security-tracker.debian.org/tracker/CVE-2018-5709)  
+  → [Red Hat CVE page](https://access.redhat.com/security/cve/cve-2018-5709)
+
+### Vulnerable Versions (Debian)
+| Release              | Version                   | Status     |
+|----------------------|----------------------------|------------|
+| bookworm              | 1.20.1-2+deb12u3              | vulnerable  |
+| sid, trixie               | 1.21.3-5             | vulnerable  |
+| bullseye             | 1.18.3-6+deb11u5           | vulnerable  |
+
+> ⚠️ These flags are **false positives** — the patch was backported, but scanners only match version numbers.
+
+### Why You Can't Fix This
+- ✅ Patch already applied by most distros through backports
+- ✅ Not exploitable beyond denial-of-service (KDC crash)
+- ✅ Modern init systems (systemd, container supervisors) automatically recover from KDC restarts
+- ❌ Replacing or manually patching `krb5` in containers is unsafe and unnecessary
+
+**✅ Recommendation:**  
+Treat CVE-2018-5709 as a **false positive** in container security reports. It does not require action if you use upstream-maintained images or system packages. Safe to ignore in nearly all production environments.
-- 
